lk to each other about the issues of the day. They find that-in settings ranging from one-on-one conversations to e-mail exchanges to larger and more formal gatherings-a surprising two-thirds of Americans regularly participate in public discussions about such pressing issues as the Iraq War, economic development, and race relations. Pinpointing the real benefits of public discourse while considering arguments that question its importance, Talking Together presents an authoritative and clear-eyed assessment of deliberation's function in American governance. In the process, it offers concrete recommendations for increasing the power of talk to foster political action.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Apr 2021) 0aDeliberative democracyzUnited States. 0aPolitical participationzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aCarpini, Michael X. Delli, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aCook, Fay Lomax, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226389899423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226389899.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles